response:
Of course, this is a graph of a Sine wave! We can also see we are only given a portion of a full period, so we can try to find how long one would take to start over. From here, using the distance formula, we can find the two points that represent half of a period, $\left(-\frac{5\pi}{3},1\right)$ and $\left(\frac{\pi}{3},1\right).$ Now, using the distance formula, we can find the length of the segment, namely 2$\pi$:  
<span style="color: #cc0000"> \begin{align*}d & = \sqrt{\left(\frac{\pi}{3} + \frac{5\pi}{3}\right)^2+(1-1)^2}\\
} & = 2\pi \end{align*}</think> <answer> $a = 2$ </answer>

